    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "<|channel>thought\n<channel|>That makes sense. So with the ARM, if the rates just keep going up and up, do I have any way to cap how high they actually go? Like is there some kind of limit so the payment doesn't just become totally unpredictable?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you can absolutely cap how high your payments go, but it's not a magic shield against the market; it's a contract with a ceiling. Most ARM lenders offer a \"rate cap,\" which is usually a percentage increase (like 5% or 6%) that the interest rate can jump by over the life of the loan.\n\nThink of it like a speed limit on a highway: the car (your mortgage) can go faster than the speed limit (the market rate), but the law (the cap) stops it from going infinitely fast. If the market rate shoots up by 10% in year 10, your ARM might only be allowed to increase by 5%, so your payment won't skyrocket to the level of a fixed-rate loan.\n\nHowever, there's a catch: if the market rate goes up by more than your cap, the lender will usually charge you a \"rate adjustment fee\" or \"breakage fee\" to cover the difference. It's like paying a toll to drive over the speed limit, but only if you're actually speeding.\n\nAlso, keep in mind that caps often apply to the *rate*, not the *payment*. If the rate goes up by 5%",
      "source": "target",
